graph.guideContent11: 1. In a computational graph display area, you can view a computational graph, zoom in or out a computational graph by scrolling the mouse wheel, and drag a computational graph.
graph.guideContent12: 2. A computational graph can be displayed in full screen or saved as an SVG file.
graph.guideContent13: 3. In the function area on the right, you can switch to view computational graphs of different files or search for nodes in a computational graph.
graph.guideContent14: 4. In the node information, you can click an input or output node to go to the selected node.
graph.guideContent2: Node types of a computational graph include namespace node, operator node, virtual node,   aggregation node, and constant node. "Default" indicates forward propagation, and "Gradients" indicates backward propagation.
graph.guideContent3: Data edges and control edges exist in a computational graph. A data edge indicates the data input, and a control edge indicates the execution dependency between node.

profiling.pipelineTopTitle: Average usage of queues between operators
profiling.iterationInfo: The step trace displays the duration of each step from the start of the previous iteration to the end of the step. The main time is divided into three parts: step interval, forward and backward propagation, and step tail.
profiling.iterationGapInfo: Reads data from data queues. If this part takes a long time, you are advised to check the data processing for further analysis.
profiling.fpbpInfo: Executes the forward and backward operators on the network, which carry the main calculation work of a step. If this part takes a long time, you are advised to check the operator statistics or timeline for further analysis.
profiling.iterativeTailingInfo: Performs parameter aggregation and update operations in multi-card scenarios. If the operations take a long time,you are advised to check the time consumed by all_reduce and the parallel status.
profiling.fpbpTimeRatio: Ratio of time consumed by forward and backward propagation:
profiling.iterationGapTimeRatio: Ratio of time consumed by step interval:
profiling.iterativeTailingTimeRatio: Ratio of time consumed by step tail:
profiling.dataProcess: This shows the data processing. Data is stored in the host queue during data processing, and then stored in the data queue on a chip during data transmission. Finally, the forward and backward propagation get_next transmits the data to forward propagation.
profiling.dataProcessInfo: By determining the empty host and data queues, you can preliminarily determine the stage where the performance is abnormal.
profiling.analysisOne: 1. If the step interval is long and some batches of the data queue on a chip are empty, the performance is abnormal during data processing and transmission. Otherwise, locate the internal problem of the forward and backward propagation get_next.
profiling.analysisTwo: 2. If the performance is abnormal during data processing and transmission, check the host queue. If the host queue is empty at a high probability, the exception may occur during data transmission.
profiling.higherAnalysis: Note: You can perform advanced analysis based on the time consumed by operators.

explain.explainSummaryCurrentFolder: Root path of the explanation log:
explain.title: Saliency Map Visualization
explain.forecastTagTip: When the inference image has the correct tag, the following four flags are displayed in the tag row
explain.TP: TP: indicates true positive. The tag is a positive sample, and the classification is a positive sample;
explain.FN: FN: indicates false negative. The tag is a positive sample, and the classification is a negative sample;
explain.FP: FP: indicates false positive. The tag is a negative sample, and the classification is a positive sample;
explain.TN: TN: indicates true negative. The tag is a negative sample, and the classification is a negative sample;
explain.mainTipPartOne: This function visualizes the basis for model classification. After the to-be-explained model, the image, and the tag are selected, a contribution degree of each pixel in the original image to the selected tag is calculated by using an explanation method, and visualization is performed by using a saliency map similar to a heatmap. A brighter color indicates that the corresponding area contributes more to the selected tag of the model prediction. The darker the color, the smaller the contribution of the area to the selected tag.
explain.mainTipPartTwo: A saliency map helps you understand the features related to the specified tag during deep neural network inference. When the inference basis and expectation of a model are different, you can debug the model by referring to the saliency map so that the model can perform inference based on proper features.
explain.mainTipPartThree: For details about how to generate saliency maps, see section 3.2 'Local Methods' in

metric.seeInterpretation: You are viewing scores of the explanation method
metric.seeMeasurement: You are viewing scores of the measurement method
metric.inputWeightScore: Enter a weight score between 0 and 1
metric.weightSumNotNull: The sum of weights cannot be empty
metric.weightSum: The sum of weights must be 1
metric.comprehensiveTooltip: The comprehensive assessment provides configurable weights for different scoring dimensions and calculates the comprehensive scores to sort and filter the explanation methods. The explanation method has advantages and disadvantages in different scoring dimensions. You can refer to the description of each dimension, adjust the weight based on the actual requirements, and assess the explanation method with emphasis. By default, weights for each dimension are the same.
metric.classifyTooltip: Classification assessment groups datasets by tag and measures the explanation methods based on data with different tags.
metric.scoreSystemtooltiptwo: The scoring system provides multiple dimensions for scoring explanation methods.
metric.scoreSystemtooltipfour: - Faithfulness: evaluates the faithfulness of the explanation result to the model, that is, whether the saliency map correctly reflects the model classification basis. Modify the corresponding positions in the original image according to a certain rule (for example, from bright to dark) and transfer the modified image to the model for inference in sequence. If the brighter the area of the saliency map is, the greater the impact on the selected tag is, the higher the faithfulness of the interpretation result is. Conversely, the explanation result may not reflect the inference basis of the model. Currently, there are three mainstream solutions: naive faithfulness, insertion AUC, and deletion AUC.
metric.scoreSystemtooltipfive: - Localization: uses the bounding box of the dataset to assess the positioning accuracy of the highlighted area in the saliency map. Select an objective and related tag. If the explanation method accurately highlights the area related to the selected tag in the image, the highlighted area should overlap the bounding box of the selected objective. Localization assesses the location capability of the explanation result by assessing the overlapped area of the highlighted area and bounding box.
